          "title": "The naming at Antioch — identity fixed to Christ alone",
          "body": "'The disciples were first called Christians in Antioch' (11:26) — Luke drops this notice with deliberate understatement. The Greek *Christianos* uses a Latin -ianus suffix (cf. *Herodianoi*, *Kaisarianoi*) — almost certainly an outsider-coinage, perhaps even mildly derogatory, to label this new movement that crossed Jewish-Gentile lines and needed a name no existing category could supply. They were not 'the Jews of Jesus' way' anymore; they were *Christ-people*, defined by allegiance to a person, not by ethnicity or rite. The name will reappear at 26:28 (Agrippa) and 1 Peter 4:16 (under persecution), and within a century will be the standard self-designation. Luke is marking the moment when the church's identity passed permanently from sub-set-of-Israel to people-of-Messiah-from-every-nation."
